INSERT INTO recipes VALUE(1525,"Lemon Marinade and Sauce for Poultry","0","PT0S","PT0S","Make and share this Lemon Marinade and Sauce for Poultry recipe from Food.com.","Poultry",4.0,2.0,391.4,23.0,4.8,0.0,3298.8,43.4,1.5,29.9,7.1,"0.0","Lemon Marinade and Sauce for Poultry Recipe Instructions:  1: Mix the cornstarch and brown sugar in a small saucepan. 2: Stir in the  remaining ingredients except the onions. 3: Blend well and heat to boiling. 4: Add the onions and immediately turn heat down. 5: Stir constantly until  sauce is thickened and bubbling. 6: Use this sauce to baste poultry during  last few minutes of grilling. 7: You can also use this sauce as a marinade. Put sauce in a heavy  plastic bag along with 2 to 3 pounds of chicken pieces and marinate for  from 2 hours to overnight, turning bag to coat all sides of meat. Use the  leftover sauce to brush on chicken while grilling. 8: This recipe doubles  nicely.");
INSERT INTO recipes VALUE(1526,"Lemon Oil Drizzle","0","PT0S","PT0S","Make and share this Lemon Oil Drizzle recipe from Food.com.","Very Low Carbs",0.0,0.0,110.1,12.4,1.7,0.0,18.4,0.1,0.0,0.1,0.0,"16.0","Lemon Oil Drizzle Recipe Instructions:  1: Add the lemon juice to the oil and mix. 2: Add the salt and pepper (herbs,  capers, etc.) and drizzle over steamed vegetables. 3: Lemon Caper Sauce:      2 tsp. 4: fresh Italian parsley, finely chopped      2 tbsp. 5: capers      1/4 tsp. 6: crushed red pepper flakes Add capers, herbs, and pepper flakes. 7: Let flavors set up for 5 minutes  before serving. 8: - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  NOTES : This incredibly simple sauce transforms cooked vegetables. 9: The  lemon brings out subtle flavors and the oil provides just enough sheen. 10: I add the salt, pepper, herbs or capers just before or as I put it on the  vegetables. 11: Make a pint or so at a time and keep it in the refrigerator. 12: Microwave  it for 10 seconds to liquefy the oil.");
INSERT INTO recipes VALUE(1527,"Linzer Bar","PT30M","PT30M","PT1H","I adopted this recipe from Recipezaar in August 2006.  I haven''t tried the recipe, but I hope to very soon.  Here is what the original poster said about this recipe: &quot;You can take one of two approaches for the top crust here - a lattice top is more traditional and a little more work - the dough can be a little crumbly so you need to add a little water to roll it out.  You can skip the lattice and simply crumble the top crust dough over the jam and bake.  It will look more like a cobbler.  Either way will taste just fine!&quot;","Bar Cookie",4.0,2.0,235.4,8.3,5.0,35.8,202.1,38.2,0.7,17.0,2.7,"12.0","Linzer Bar Recipe Instructions:  1: In a large bowl stir together flour, sugar, brown sugar, baking  powder, salt and cinnamon. 2: With a pastry blender or two knives use scissor  style, cut in butter or margarine until coarse crumbs form. 3: With a fork stir  in corn syrup and egg just until mixed. 4: Reserve 1/2 cup batter. 5: Press  remaining batter into a 9x9x2-inch baking pan. 6: spread with jam. 7: Stir 2  tablespoons flour into the reserved batter. 8: If preparing a lattice add a couple tablespoons of water - one at a time - to make the dough easy to roll out.  If you are dropping the dough by spoonfulls then just evenly scatter the top \ 9:  over the jam for a \ 10:  look and bake. 11: On a floured surface roll out to  1/4-inch thickness. 12: Cut into 1/4-inch wide strips. 13: Lattice strips over jam. 14: Bake in 375-degree oven 30 minutes, or until set. Cool. 15: Cut into bars. Serving size is really up to you - cut into as many bars as you want.");
